-- Japanese Stock Futures Fall, Australian Shares Little Changed
-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 2010-12-09T23:41:41Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-09/japanese-stock-futures-retreat-on-euro-australian-shares-little-changed.html
Japanese  stock   futures  declined as a
downgrade to Ireland’s credit rating fueled concern Europe’s
debt crisis will spread and as the euro weakened. Australian
shares were little changed.  American depositary receipts of Sumitomo Mitsui Financial
Group Inc., Japan’s second-biggest bank, lost 0.7 percent from
the closing share price in Tokyo. Honda Motor Co., a carmaker
that get about 80 percent of its sales abroad, declined 0.7
percent and those of Canon Inc., the world’s biggest camera
maker, slid 0.3 percent after the euro weakened.  BHP Billiton
Ltd. , the world’s largest mining company, fell 0.4 percent today
in Sydney.  “Investors are concerned European debt issues will
worsen,” said  Juichi Wako , a senior strategist at Tokyo-based
Nomura Holdings Inc. “Investors may sell exporters, which led
market gains in November, on the weaker euro against the yen.”  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 Stock Average  expiring in
December closed at 10,255 in Chicago yesterday, compared with
10,275 in Singapore. They were bid in the pre-market at 10,250
in Osaka at 8:05 a.m. local time today. Australia’s S&P/ASX 200
Index was little changed in Sydney today. New Zealand’s NZX 50
Index fell 0.1 percent in Wellington.  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  gained 0.2
percent. Yesterday, the index climbed 0.4 percent to a two-year
high for the second straight day, after Pacific Investment
Management Co., the operator of the world’s largest bond fund,
raised its forecast for economic growth and U.S. jobless claims
dropped.  Applications for  unemployment benefits  fell to 421,000 from
a revised 438,000 the prior week, Labor Department figures
showed yesterday.  Weaker Euro, Metal  The euro declined against 12 of its 16 most-traded
counterparts after a downgrade to Ireland’s credit rating added
to concern Europe’s debt crisis may spread.  Ireland’s credit rating was cut three levels by Fitch
Ratings to the lowest of any of the major rating companies after
the country sought international assistance last month to rescue
its banks.  The yen appreciated to as high as 110.59 against the euro
today in Tokyo, compared with 111.55 at the close of stock
trading yesterday. Against the dollar, Japan’s currency
strengthened to 83.52 from 83.83. A stronger yen reduces
overseas income at Japanese companies when converted into their
home currency.  Copper prices for March delivery fell in New York on
speculation that China, the world’s biggest metal consumer, may
raise interest rates to slow economic growth and inflation. The
 London Metal Exchange Index  of six metals including copper and
aluminum slipped 0.8 percent yesterday, the first drop in four
days.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index climbed 11 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with gains of 11 percent by the
Standard & Poor’s 500 Index and 8.7 percent by the Stoxx Europe
600 Index. Shares in the Asian benchmark are valued at 14.7
times  estimated earnings  on average, compared with 14.5 times
for the S&P 500 and 12.3 times for the Stoxx 600.  To contact the reporters on this story:
